post_text:
At 9:05am on September 11, 2001 President George W Bush, was observing a Direct Instruction classroom of 2nd Grade students. An advisor quietly interrupted to inform the President that a plane had struck the World Trade Center.

Our world would be changed forever.

The days that followed showed much of what was (and is) great about America. Americans stood united. Any divisions, real or perceived, were set aside. Flags proudly flew outside millions of businesses and homes.

post_text:
Great information: The Importance of Reopening America’s Schools this Fall

"Scientific studies suggest that COVID-19 transmission among children in schools may be low. International studies that have assessed how readily COVID-19 spreads in schools also reveal low rates of transmission when community transmission is low. Based on current data, the rate of infection among younger school children, and from students to teachers, has been low, especially if proper precautions are followed."

Well-Being Wednesday activities are optional. A table set up in front of the school with packets ready for school families to pick up between 8:30am-noon on Wednesdays (or Thursdays!). Wednesday April 22: Let’s Plant a Garden! (Wildflower seeds, sunflower seeds, bean seeds, and corn seeds!)

Wednesday April 29: Let’s Create Some Art!- Option of Watercolors or Oil Pastels (And any leftover from the previous week)

Wednesday May 6: Let’s Write a Letter! (And any leftovers from previous weeks)

post_text:
Countless studies and articles confirm that Common Core isn't working. Sadly, the vast majority of schools continue to follow it, and some schools are even choosing to adopt it! Why? A major reason is due to state tests relying heavily upon NC Standards/Common Core. We've had the opportunity to speak with a number of schools that were pressured to drop their proven, effective curricula in favor of Common Core because of the alignment between state testing and common core standards. At our school, we put students first. Our curriculum is designed to awaken a love for education, foster character development, and encourage critical thinking.

While NC bureaucrats are busy training schools on effective test writing, such as eliminating words like "make", "fair", "park", "not", and "except" from testing questions, we are busy educating the leaders of tomorrow.

post_text:
Usborne will be hosting a Book Fair on February 19th from 4:00-6:30pm. The sales in the past have only had $5.00 selections. This book fair, however, will include a wider range of titles, authors, and reading levels. The book prices will range from $3.99 and up. We are excited that students and families will have a wider selection of books to choose from!

The book sale is scheduled for after school so that parents and families can peruse the selection together. Parents or guardians must attend with their YA student at this book fair. The time range between 4:00-6:30pm will allow families to come when they are able and should spread us out enough so that ample parking is available.

Payment options:

Tax is additional. Acceptable payment options: cash, cards, and checks (to Usborne Books & More).

Click here to save it to your calendar: https://www.youngsvilleacademy.org/apps/events/2020/2/19/7856544/?REC_ID=7856544&id=0

post_text:
We are very happy to report that our students did exceptionally well on their Iowa Tests!

Our students significantly outperformed their average national peers (at each grade level) and demonstrated significant growth over their previous year's scores (at each grade level)!

The average student who takes the Iowas will receive a National Percentile Rank of 50. North Carolina traditionally scores around average, with Franklin County traditionally scoring slightly below average.

Three years ago our average students performed at a remarkable 59.5, showing that the average YA student was nearly 10 points higher than their average peers who scored 50. The following year YA improved to 62.2 and this year our average jumped all the way to 69.

We are so proud of our students for this accomplishment!

We are excited about their continued growth and what this means for them and for their futures.

Thank you for entrusting your student's education to Youngsville Academy!

post_text: A great reminder about what a healthy lunch looks like, by Madison, one of our 5th Grader students: "The lunch should include a healthy snack such as veggies, like carrots or celery. It should also have fruits, like strawberries and blueberries. It is important to pack a healthy lunch, because as kids we need nourishment to live and grow. For lunch you need something like a sandwich with healthy things in it. Some healthy things like lettuce, tomatoes, and onions. Of course as kids, we naturally gravitate towards sweet things for a treat, but not a whole lunch of them. It also would be smart to trade Doritos for Veggie Straws. Some ways you can have a healthier lunch is to eat a healthy dinner that you can eat for lunch the next day. Finally, you can get rid of most of your junk food. These are ways you could have a healthier lunch."
